    "narrative": "For today's slate, **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) and **Corbin Carroll** (72.32) headline our daily efficiency rankings. **Mickey Moniak** is our primary offensive engine, buoyed by an elite matchup against Sasaki, where park factors and an optimal #2 spot in the order maximize his output. Similarly, **Corbin Carroll** remains a mandatory start despite facing a high-caliber arm in Gausman; his dynamic platoon advantage and top-tier sprint speed\u2014essential for our scarcity-driven strategy\u2014keep his floor high even against tough pitching. **Tyler Soderstrom** (70.03) and **Max Muncy** (68.95) also grade out as strong starts, largely capitalizing on the favorable xERA profile of Schultz, which provides the necessary leverage for our mid-to-bottom order to exceed typical daily expectations.\n\nOur most difficult personnel decision centered on **Alex Freeland**, who posted a 53.65 score but narrowly missed the cut behind **Vinnie Pasquantino** and **Austin Riley**. While **Alex Freeland** benefits from favorable park factors, his bottom-of-the-order positioning (-8%) ultimately suppressed his ceiling compared to the primary lineup. We also continue to monitor **James Wood** (68.56) and **Seiya Suzuki** (63.03); although both face potential resistance from elite catchers with quick pop times (1.86s\u20131.87s), their overall offensive environments and high-leverage lineup slots allow them to maintain \"Strong\" start designations. Conversely, **Luis Campusano** was an easy exclusion today, falling well below our 40.0 floor due to a brutal matchup against Urena and a projected #8 spot, reinforcing our strict discipline in preserving game caps for high-efficiency opportunities.\n\nRisk management remains a priority given that we are navigating a slate with several high-skill pitchers. We have flagged **Vinnie Pasquantino** (53.63) as a marginal start; while his raw talent is undeniable, the dynamic platoon disadvantage against Weathers creates enough volatility that we are prioritizing his inclusion only because he occupies a prime #3 spot. Similarly, while **Trevor Story** (57.63) receives a boost from his potential to swipe bags against Valdez, he remains a candidate for mid-game substitution if his defensive metrics or early plate appearances signal a lack of rhythm against the lefty. With **Josh Naylor** out of the lineup entirely, we are banking on the depth of our outfield corps to carry the offensive load tonight.",
